    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Right, that's why the inspections are so important. It's kind of crazy how something as tiny as an insect or a bit of grit can basically blind the pilot to how fast they're actually going. Is there anything else besides physical blockages that can mess with the pressure readings or the accuracy of the instruments?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, beyond physical blockages, several other factors can introduce inaccuracies into the pitot-static system. A significant source of error is incorrect altimeter setting, which affects the static pressure reference. Furthermore, icing outside the range of the heated pitot system, or damage to the probes themselves, can skew the pressure readings. These issues can cause erratic or consistently wrong airspeed and altitude indications.",
      "source": "target",
